The grammar contains many mutually-recursive, cyclic rules (e.g. NT1 ↔ NT9, NT7 ↔ NT8, NT0 ↔ NT7, etc.).  
Every terminal symbol that appears in the test string is produced directly by at least one non-terminal in the grammar:

t19, t26  →  NT3  
t28       →  NT9  
t14, t4   →  NT7 (or NT2 for t4)  
t32       →  NT4  
t24       →  NT6  
t9        →  NT0  

Because all of these non-terminals participate in cycles that can freely generate additional non-terminals (each of which can again expand in two branches, thanks to Chomsky-normal productions such as NT1 → NT9 NT1, NT7 → NT8 NT7, NT0 → NT0 NT7, etc.), the grammar can build binary derivation trees of arbitrary size whose leaves are any sequence of the above terminals, in any order and in any quantity.

Consequently, there is no structural or length restriction that prevents the specific 37-token string given from being derived. The required non-terminals can be generated in the needed order and finally rewritten to the exact terminals of the string.

Therefore the string is in the language generated by the grammar.

Yes
